MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Five PGCL sub-page sites in mm/memory.c computed the sub-PAGE index
within a kernel page from `pgoff_sub_page_index(vma->vm_pgoff +
((addr - vm_start) >> MMUPAGE_SHIFT))`, implicitly assuming
vma->vm_pgoff mod PAGE_MMUCOUNT tracks vm_start >> MMUPAGE_SHIFT.

That invariant is established for anon VMAs by insert_vm_struct and
preserved by mremap, but **deliberately not** by relocate_vma_down (the
temp-stack-relocation path), where move_page_tables keeps the
underlying pages at their original physical sub-PAGE alignment.  When
the new vm_start lands at a different mod-PAGE_MMUCOUNT offset than
the old vm_start, the pgoff-based sub gives a value off by the
delta, and:

  - In the COW clustering loop (do_wp_page → wp_page_copy), the
    wrong `sub` is used to rewind `vmf->pte - sub` to "the start of
    this kernel page in the PTE table".  When sub is too large by N,
    base_pte points N * sizeof(pte_t) BEFORE the actual PTE table,
    landing in another allocation (typically user stack content).
    ptep_get reads "AAAA..." (the user's stack data), pte_present
    accepts it, pte_pfn yields a garbage PFN, and the subsequent
    page_folio(pte_page(pteval)) dereferences an unmapped vmemmap
    slot — kernel panic.

  - In wp_page_copy / copy_present_page's single-PTE adjustment, the
    new PTE is pointed at the wrong sub-PAGE of the new folio.
    Since __wp_page_copy_user / copy_user_highpage copies
    sub-page-for-sub-page, this returns wrong content to the user
    (typically a SIGSEGV with rip=0 because a function pointer was
    read from the wrong offset).

The sub-PAGE position is a property of the address space layout, not
of pgoff:

  - For PTE-table indexing (base_pte/base_addr in the clustering
    loops), use ADDRESS-based sub:
      sub = (addr >> MMUPAGE_SHIFT) & (PAGE_MMUCOUNT - 1)

  - For preserving COW content sub-PAGE in the new folio, read it
    directly from the OLD PTE via pte_suboffset(), which already
    encodes the correct physical sub-PAGE.

  - For fresh anonymous allocations (do_anonymous_page clustering),
    the new folio has no prior assignment so address-based sub gives
    a consistent virtual-to-folio mapping.

  - set_pte_range (file fault path) is intentionally unchanged: file
    mappings legitimately use the pgoff-based sub because vm_pgoff
    *is* the file offset, and the folio sub-PAGE matches the file
    offset's sub-PAGE position.

pte_suboffset's generic implementation assumed __phys_to_pte_val is
identity (true for x86/s390/arm64), which silently returned the wrong
bits on mips (PFN at bit 6) — fix it to go through __pte_val_to_phys,
and add a generic __pte_val_to_phys fallback for parity with
__phys_to_pte_val.

Verified clean on x86_64 / s390x / aarch64 / mips64 at PGCL=6
(was: 10 BUGs + do_wp_page panic / 0 / 9 BUGs + same panic / init
SIGSEGV respectively prior to this commit).

Signed-off-by: Nadia Yvette Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@gmail.com>
---
 include/linux/pgtable.h | 20 ++++++++---
 mm/memory.c             | 79 +++++++++++++++++++++++++++--------------
 2 files changed, 69 insertions(+), 30 deletions(-)

diff --git a/include/linux/pgtable.h b/include/linux/pgtable.h
index ed73b2611fde..36c6b672d50d 100644
--- a/include/linux/pgtable.h
+++ b/include/linux/pgtable.h
@@ -398,6 +398,16 @@ static inline pte_t pte_advance_pfn(pte_t pte, unsigned long nr)
 #define __phys_to_pte_val(phys)	(phys)
 #endif
 
+/*
+ * Inverse of __phys_to_pte_val.  Identity on archs where the PTE PFN field
+ * is a direct physical address (x86, s390 etc).  Archs where the encoding
+ * differs (mips PFN at bit 6, riscv _PAGE_PFN_SHIFT != MMUPAGE_SHIFT) must
+ * override this together with __phys_to_pte_val.
+ */
+#ifndef __pte_val_to_phys
+#define __pte_val_to_phys(val)	(val)
+#endif
+
 #ifndef set_ptes
 /**
  * set_ptes - Map consecutive pages to a contiguous range of addresses.
@@ -1082,11 +1092,13 @@ static inline pte_t pte_mksub(pte_t pte, unsigned long offset)
 static inline unsigned long pte_suboffset(pte_t pte)
 {
 #if PAGE_MMUSHIFT
-	/* NOTE: assumes __phys_to_pte_val(x) == x (true for x86).
-	 * Arches where PTE PFN encoding differs (e.g. riscv) should
-	 * override this.
+	/*
+	 * Convert the PTE's PFN field back to a physical address (identity
+	 * on most archs; mips/riscv encode PFN at a different bit position
+	 * and override __pte_val_to_phys), then mask out everything except
+	 * the sub-page bits within a kernel page.
 	 */
-	return (pte_val(pte) & (PAGE_SIZE - 1)) & MMUPAGE_MASK;
+	return __pte_val_to_phys(pte_val(pte)) & (PAGE_SIZE - 1) & MMUPAGE_MASK;
 #else
 	return 0;
 #endif
diff --git a/mm/memory.c b/mm/memory.c
index f9b436b7c339..e44414628898 100644
--- a/mm/memory.c
+++ b/mm/memory.c
@@ -1091,15 +1091,15 @@ copy_present_page(struct vm_area_struct *dst_vma, struct vm_area_struct *src_vma
 	/* All done, just insert the new page copy in the child */
 	pte = folio_mk_pte(new_folio, dst_vma->vm_page_prot);
 	/*
-	 * With PAGE_MMUSHIFT > 0, adjust PTE to the correct MMUPAGE
-	 * within the copied page.
+	 * With PAGE_MMUSHIFT > 0, the new (copied) folio must be
+	 * pointed at the same sub-PAGE as the source PTE pointed to,
+	 * because copy_user_highpage copies sub-PAGE-for-sub-PAGE.
+	 * Read the sub-PAGE offset from the source PTE rather than
+	 * recomputing it from vma->vm_pgoff (which may diverge from
+	 * vm_start>>MMUPAGE_SHIFT after relocate_vma_down or mremap).
 	 */
-	if (PAGE_MMUSHIFT > 0) {
-		pgoff_t pgoff = dst_vma->vm_pgoff +
-			((addr - dst_vma->vm_start) >> MMUPAGE_SHIFT);
-		unsigned int sub = pgoff_sub_page_index(pgoff);
-		pte = __pte(pte_val(pte) + __phys_to_pte_val((phys_addr_t)sub * MMUPAGE_SIZE));
-	}
+	if (PAGE_MMUSHIFT > 0)
+		pte = __pte(pte_val(pte) + __phys_to_pte_val(pte_suboffset(ptep_get(src_pte))));
 	pte = maybe_mkwrite(pte_mkdirty(pte), dst_vma);
 	if (userfaultfd_pte_wp(dst_vma, ptep_get(src_pte)))
 		/* Uffd-wp needs to be delivered to dest pte as well */
@@ -4093,16 +4093,17 @@ static vm_fault_t wp_page_copy(struct vm_fault *vmf)
 		flush_cache_page(vma, vmf->address, pte_pfn(vmf->orig_pte));
 		entry = folio_mk_pte(new_folio, vma->vm_page_prot);
 		/*
-		 * With PAGE_MMUSHIFT > 0, adjust PTE to point to the correct
-		 * MMUPAGE within the new page (same sub-page offset as the
-		 * original mapping).
+		 * With PAGE_MMUSHIFT > 0, the new PTE must point to the same
+		 * sub-PAGE of the new folio as the old PTE pointed to of the
+		 * old folio — __wp_page_copy_user copied the whole old folio
+		 * to the new one sub-PAGE-for-sub-PAGE.  Take the sub-PAGE
+		 * offset from the original PTE rather than from vma->vm_pgoff
+		 * (which may diverge from vm_start>>MMUPAGE_SHIFT after
+		 * relocate_vma_down or mremap).
 		 */
-		if (PAGE_MMUSHIFT > 0) {
-			pgoff_t pgoff = vma->vm_pgoff +
-				((vmf->address - vma->vm_start) >> MMUPAGE_SHIFT);
-			unsigned int sub = pgoff_sub_page_index(pgoff);
-			entry = __pte(pte_val(entry) + __phys_to_pte_val((phys_addr_t)sub * MMUPAGE_SIZE));
-		}
+		if (PAGE_MMUSHIFT > 0)
+			entry = __pte(pte_val(entry) +
+				      __phys_to_pte_val(pte_suboffset(vmf->orig_pte)));
 		entry = pte_sw_mkyoung(entry);
 		if (unlikely(unshare)) {
 			if (pte_soft_dirty(vmf->orig_pte))
@@ -4165,9 +4166,21 @@ static vm_fault_t wp_page_copy(struct vm_fault *vmf)
 		 * same folio.
 		 */
 		if (old_folio && folio_test_anon(old_folio) && !unshare) {
-			pgoff_t pgoff = vma->vm_pgoff +
-				((vmf->address - vma->vm_start) >> MMUPAGE_SHIFT);
-			unsigned int sub = pgoff_sub_page_index(pgoff);
+			/*
+			 * base_pte / base_addr index the PTE table and the
+			 * address space, so sub must be the ADDRESS-based
+			 * sub-PAGE position within the kernel page.  Using
+			 * vma->vm_pgoff would assume it tracks vm_start mod
+			 * PAGE_MMUCOUNT, but relocate_vma_down() preserves
+			 * the OLD vm_pgoff (so the OLD physical sub-PAGE
+			 * mapping survives move_page_tables), and that
+			 * pgoff-based sub does NOT match the new PTE table
+			 * layout.  Each replaced PTE's *content* sub-PAGE
+			 * (where it points inside the new folio) is preserved
+			 * separately via pte_suboffset(pteval) below.
+			 */
+			unsigned int sub = (vmf->address >> MMUPAGE_SHIFT) &
+					   (PAGE_MMUCOUNT - 1);
 			pte_t *base_pte = vmf->pte - sub;
 			unsigned long base_addr = vmf->address -
 					(unsigned long)sub * MMUPAGE_SIZE;
@@ -4201,12 +4214,18 @@ static vm_fault_t wp_page_copy(struct vm_fault *vmf)
 				    old_folio)
 					continue;
 
-				/* Clear+flush old, set new */
+				/*
+				 * Preserve the OLD PTE's sub-PAGE offset:
+				 * __wp_page_copy_user copied the entire old
+				 * folio to the new folio sub-PAGE-for-sub-PAGE,
+				 * so the new PTE must point to the SAME
+				 * sub-PAGE of new_folio as old PTE pointed to
+				 * of old_folio.
+				 */
 				ptep_clear_flush(vma, a, ptep);
 				set_pte_at(mm, a, ptep,
 					   pte_mksub(base_entry,
-						     (unsigned long)j *
-						     MMUPAGE_SIZE));
+						     pte_suboffset(pteval)));
 				folio_remove_rmap_pte(old_folio,
 						      pte_page(pteval), vma);
 				extra++;
@@ -5884,9 +5903,17 @@ static vm_fault_t do_anonymous_page(struct vm_fault *vmf)
 		 * divides PTRS_PER_PTE evenly.
 		 */
 		pte_t entry;
-		unsigned int sub = pgoff_sub_page_index(
-			vma->vm_pgoff +
-			((vmf->address - vma->vm_start) >> MMUPAGE_SHIFT));
+		/*
+		 * Fresh allocation: this is a brand new folio with no prior
+		 * sub-PAGE assignment, so the ADDRESS-based sub-PAGE position
+		 * works for both the PTE table indexing and the folio sub-PAGE
+		 * mapping (we map address-sub-PAGE-j to folio-sub-PAGE-j).
+		 * Using vma->vm_pgoff would silently assume it tracks
+		 * vm_start>>MMUPAGE_SHIFT, which relocate_vma_down does not
+		 * preserve.
+		 */
+		unsigned int sub = (vmf->address >> MMUPAGE_SHIFT) &
+				   (PAGE_MMUCOUNT - 1);
 		pte_t *base_pte = vmf->pte - sub;
 		unsigned long base_addr = addr - (unsigned long)sub * MMUPAGE_SIZE;
 		unsigned long rss = 0;
